        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> <img alt=\"Image\" width=\"541\" height=\"1275\" src=\"https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/416322/597350785-76aacf70-005a-4d43-a888-5850b119aaf0.jpg?jwt=eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9.eyJpc3MiOiJnaXRodWIuY29tIiwiYXVkIjoicmF3LmdpdGh1YnVzZXJjb250ZW50LmNvbSIsImtleSI6ImtleTUiLCJleHAiOjE3Nzk4OTMxMjksIm5iZiI6MTc3OTg5MjgyOSwicGF0aCI6Ii80MTYzMjIvNTk3MzUwNzg1LTc2YWFjZjcwLTAwNWEtNGQ0My1hODg4LTU4NTBiMTE5YWFmMC5qcGc_.AqJmPbQr7JN_FyuT-wFgCvpg7s_BGZ_8pLyncqYiAvs\">\n\nDisplaying code lenses on a new line can be beneficial in this type of situation. This image shows an extreme case where variable names are very short; if the names were slightly longer, the `n ref` would align with multiple variable names on the same line.\n\n> Analogous to how `on_list` is a very generic way to override \"list\" behavior of `vim.lsp.buf.references()`, `vim.lsp.buf.implementation()`, etc. Also related: `vim.Scope` [#39570 (comment)](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/39570#discussion_r3207324542)\n\nWhile exposing a callback would be great, getting these extmarks to display is not that simple. For example, both inlay hints and code lenses cache lines that have already been displayed—it's not just a simple `set_extmark`. Code lenses also include logic to debounce during the resolve process. It is difficult to expose a suitable API that would allow users to achieve the same level of functionality as nvim's built-in implementation.\n\nAnother idea is to implement an API that wraps `set_decoration_provider` (#39438). High-level wrappers for low-level APIs would likely be very popular; for instance, `vim.lsp.util.open_floating_preview` is a wrapper for `open_win` that is widely used outside of LSP contexts.\n\n\n",
