        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> I guess my confusion is that it seems the default was virtual text and then in the recent update it was changed to virtual line(s). I am curious what prompted the default change? If a boolean flag isn't acceptable, is there a way to opt out of the default somehow without having to move back to `0.11`?\n\nSome LSP servers heavily relied on the assumption that code lenses displayed on virtual lines, e.g., https://haskell-language-server.readthedocs.io/en/stable/features.html#evaluation-code-snippets-in-comments. This assumption should be very common; many editors that support code lenses implement it this way. \n\nBefore the new implementation in 0.12, `vim.lsp.codelens` requires users to call `refresh()` in an autocmd to refresh code lenses. This means that if we display code lenses on virtual lines, the text layout would shift up and down as code lenses appear and disappear after every `refresh()` call.\n\nIn the new implementation, nvim takes over more to show code lenses so that we can handle these edge cases. The old method was deemed a compromise, so it now defaults to showing on virtual lines.",
